    <div class="prose-tca">

      <section>
        <h2>How I Evaluated the Gesture at 6'4"</h2>
        <p>My roommate owns a Steelcase Gesture, which gave me an extended hands-on session to work through a systematic evaluation at my height. I came at this with a Mechanical Engineering background — which means I care less about whether a chair "feels comfortable" in the showroom and more about whether the dimensional math holds up for bodies outside the design median.</p>
        <p>For context: at 6'4", I have a 32–33" inseam and a proportionally long torso. Those proportions put me right at the Gesture's dimensional ceiling. What I was specifically testing: how the maximum seat depth of 18.75" interacts with my thigh length, where the 24" backrest actually makes contact on my spine, and whether the 360° armrest system translates to real-world posture support at a standard 30" desk setup.</p>
        <p>The comparison baseline throughout this review is the <a href="/gesture-vs-leap-plus/" class="link-internal">Steelcase Leap Plus</a> — the obvious alternative for tall users who need more dimensional range — and the <a href="/aeron-vs-gesture/" class="link-internal">Herman Miller Aeron Size C</a>, which targets the same user but with a fundamentally different design philosophy.</p>
